<subSubSection id="209BF388FFF6CA0E48BDE340FB65CDB7" box="[199,1260,871,896]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="683EA003FFF6CA0E48BDE340FB65CDB7" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1077]" box="[199,1260,871,896]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">
<emphasis id="5AF57C11FFF6CA0E48BDE340FEC7CDB7" bold="true" box="[199,334,871,896]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name refers to the 
<collectingRegion id="AA456EE1FFF6CA0E4ACFE340FC86CDB7" box="[693,783,871,896]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
province where the species was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="209BF388FFF6CA0E48BDE3ABFB51CDDA" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="683EA003FFF6CA0E48BDE3ABFB51CDDA" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1077]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">
<emphasis id="5AF57C11FFF6CA0E48BDE3ABFEE9CD92" bold="true" box="[199,352,908,933]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is known from two localities in the northern mountains of 
<collectingRegion id="AA456EE1FFF6CA0E4CFCE3ABFB69CD92" box="[1158,1248,908,933]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
and one locality in 
<collectingRegion id="AA456EE1FFF6CA0E48CCE388FEA6CDFF" box="[182,303,943,968]" country="Guatemala" name="Guatemala" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">
<collectingCountry id="1096E093FFF6CA0E48CCE388FEA6CDFF" box="[182,303,943,968]" name="Guatemala" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
inside the Cuchumatanes mountain range. It is associated with pine-oak forests that dominate the region; unfortunately, most of these forests have been transformed to coffee plantations (
<figureCitation id="F0BABC86FFF6CA0E4C02E3F3FB42CDDA" box="[1144,1227,980,1005]" captionStart="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[514,1092,1007,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[470,1116,949,1856]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57 — Map of collecting localities for Colletes jobeli, C. isabelae, C. jaliscoensis and C. nigerrima. 58 — Map of collecting localities for C. solari, C. tzotzilis, C. chiaPensis, and C. guatemalensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1051949/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="209BF388FFF6CA0E48BDE3D0FBD9CA02" pageId="10" pageNumber="411" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="683EA003FFF6CA0E48BDE3D0FBD9CA02" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1077]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">
<emphasis id="5AF57C11FFF6CA0E48BDE3D0FEB2CA27" bold="true" box="[199,315,1015,1040]" pageId="10" pageNumber="411">Remarks.</emphasis>
In some female specimens, the elevation on supraclypeal area may have some deep but sparse punctures. Scutellum punctures in some specimens are less deep and more separated.
</paragraph>
